04415nam a22007215i 9781442682849DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20162004onc    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)1013950362  a97814426828497 a10.3138/97814426828492doi  a(DE-B1597)465068  a(OCoLC)944177276  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  aonccCA-ON 4aHG8054.5 7aSOC0260002bisacsh04a3681 aDoyle, Aaron, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aUncertain Business :bRisk, Insurance, and the Limits of Knowledge /cAaron Doyle, Diana Ericson. 1aToronto : bUniversity of Toronto Press, c[2016] 4cÂ©2004  a1 online resource (335 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- t1 Risk, Insurance, and the Limits of Knowledge -- t2 Uncertainties of Life: Embracing Risk, Prudence, and Investment -- t3 Uncertainties of Disability: Spreading Risk, Solidarity, and Welfare -- t4 Uncertainties of Earthquakes: Absorbing Risk, Mitigation, and Infrastructure -- t5 Uncertainties of Terrorism: Pre-Empting Risk, Precaution, and Vigilance -- t6 Uncertain Business -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWe live in an age of increasing doubt about whether our institutions and technologies can provide security against risks, many of which they themselves have created. Uncertain Business is an unprecedented inquiry into insurance industry practices and what they tell us about risks and uncertainties in contemporary society.The core of the book is ethnographic studies in distinct fields of insurance: premature death, disability, earthquake, and terrorism. These studies reveal that uncertainty pervades different fields of insurance, the very industry that is charged with transforming uncertainty into manageable risk. Scientific data on risk are variously absent, inadequate, controversial, contradictory, and ignored. Insurers impose meaning on uncertainty through non-scientific forms of knowledge that are intuitive, emotional, aesthetic, moral, and speculative. Nevertheless, the nature of uncertainty and the response to it varies substantially across the fields studied, showing how contemporary society is characterized by competing risk logics.Insurers' perceptions and decisions about uncertainty ? with potential for windfall profits as well as catastrophic losses ? create crises in insurance availability and provoke new forms of inequality and exclusion. Hence, while the insurance industry is a central bulwark against uncertainty, insurers also play a key role in fostering it.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aRisk (Insurance). 0aTechnologyxSociological aspects. 0aUncertainty. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / General.2bisacsh1 aEricson, Diana, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311049095440uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978144268284940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781442682849423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781442682849.jpg  a978-3-11-049095-4  University of Toronto Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK